---


Author Name: **Julius Baxter** (@juliusbaxter)
Original Redmine Message: 923 from https://www.veripool.org



---

I'd like to get a clarification for the reason for the following error:

 Unsupported: Non-constant inside []'s in the cell part of a dotted reference

Upon googling the error it links to issue #517, http://www.veripool.org/issues/517-Verilator-Constant-expression-in-generated-block-index-not-recognized


#517 looks like it's an issue with addressing multiple instances, however I'm seeing the error being caused when attempting to select a struct from an array of them, and then one of the struct's members. The following is a testcase:
```
package TEST_TYPES;
    typedef struct packed {
       logic   stuff;     
    } a_struct;
endpackage // TEST_TYPES

module testmodule(a_out);
    parameter n = 4;
    output TEST_TYPES::a_struct [n-1:0] a_out;
    always_comb
      begin
	for (int i=0;i<n;i++)
	  a_out[i].stuff = '0;
      end
endmodule // testmodule

```

I compile with:

 verilator -sv --lint-only testcase.sv

and get:

 %Error: testcase.sv:13: Unsupported: Non-constant inside []'s in the cell part of a dotted reference
 %Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)

Is this the expected behaviour for this code?

If so..... any idea when support for such a thing will be added, and how hard it would be?

Thanks

